`WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` relies on Android's deprecated `adjustResize`, which no longer works reliably (especially with edge-to-edge enforced in Android 15+).

**.NET MAUI .NET 8+ includes `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`**, enabled by default, which auto-scrolls focused inputs into view. However, for a chat layout (input pinned to the bottom, messages above), you typically need manual inset handling.

### Recommended approach for a chat screen:

**1. In `MainActivity.cs`, set `AdjustResize` and handle insets:**

```csharp
[Activity(Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
          WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustResize,
          // ...other attributes
          )]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
}
```

**2. Use a `Grid` layout with the input bar at the bottom:**

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0"
                    ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}"
                    ItemsUpdatingScrollMode="KeepLastItemInView">
        <!-- message templates -->
    </CollectionView>

    <Grid Grid.Row="1" Padding="8" ColumnDefinitions="*, Auto">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." />
        <Button Grid.Column="1" Text="Send" />
    </Grid>
</Grid>
```

**3. If the auto-manager interferes, disconnect it and handle insets yourself:**

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnCreate((activity, _) =>
        {
            // Disable MAUI's auto-scroll — we handle it via AdjustResize
            Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll
                .Disconnect();

            // Ensure edge-to-edge insets are applied so AdjustResize
            // still shrinks the window above the keyboard
            AndroidX.Core.View.ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
                activity.Window!.DecorView,
                new InsetListener());
        }));
#endif
});
```

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using AndroidX.Core.View;
class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
        Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var sysInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max(keyboard, nav bar)
        v.SetPadding(
            sysInsets.Left, sysInsets.Top, sysInsets.Right,
            Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, sysInsets.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
#endif
```

### TL;DR

| Approach | When to use |
|---|---|
| **Do nothing** (default `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`) | Simple forms with scrollable content |
| **`AdjustResize` + insets listener** (above) | Chat screens with a pinned bottom input bar |

The insets-based approach works with Android 15's enforced edge-to-edge mode and replaces the old `Resize` behavior reliably.
